'''Robert Francis Catterson''' (March 22, 1835 &ndash; March 30, 1914) was an [[United States|American]] soldier. He served as a [[Union Army]] [[General officer|general]] during the [[American Civil War]].<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Find A Grave">{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GRid=18126|title=Robert Francis Catterson|accessdate=16 November 2008|publisher=[[Find A Grave]]}}</ref> 

==Early life==
Catterson was born on March 22, 1835, on a farm near Beech Grove, Marion County, Indiana.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies">{{cite web |url=http://civilwarindiana.com/biographies/catterson_robert_francis.html |title=Robert Francis Catterson |accessdate=22 November 2008 |publisher=Civil War Indiana Biographies}}</ref> He was the son of an Irish immigrant. He was studied at Adrian College in Michigan and Cincinnati Medical College. After completing his medical studies, he practiced medicine in Rockville, Indiana.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/>

==Civil War service==
After the Civil War started, he gave up his established medical practice and enlisted in the 14th Indiana Volunteer Infantry Regiment. He was mustered into Company A of the 14th Indiana Infantry on April 23, 1861.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> He became first sergeant in June, second lieutenant in July, first lieutenant the following March, and captain in May 1862. He served in western Virginia and saw action at Kernstown, in the [[Valley Campaign]], and the [[Battle of Antietam]].<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> Catterson was appointed lieutenant colonel of the 97th Indiana on October 18, 1862. He became colonel the following month.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> He served at Memphis. He took part in the [[siege of Vicksburg]], the [[Tullahoma Campaign]], the [[Battle of Chattanooga]], the [[Atlanta Campaign]], and [[Sherman's March to the Sea]].<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> When [[William Tecumseh Sherman]] started the [[Carolinas Campaign]], he was given a brigade in the XV Corps and saw action at Bentonville, North Carolina, the last major engagement of the Civil War.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Find A Grave"/> He was brevetted brigadier general of US Volunteers on May 31, 1865, and was mustered out of the service on January 15, 1866.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> 

==Postbellum==
After the Civil War, Catterson didn't practice medicine.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Find A Grave"/> After failing in cotton speculation, he became commander of the Arkansas Negro militia under Governor [[Powell Clayton]] to fight against the [[Ku Klux Klan]].<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> He was the mayor of Little Rock, Arkansas from 1872&ndash;74.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> After serving as mayor, he moved to Minnesota. In Minnesota, he was an unsuccessful farmer and farm implement merchant. He died in the Veterans<U+2019> Hospital in San Antonio, Texas on March 30, 1914 after suffering from a stroke, and he was buried in the National Cemetery there.<ref name="Robert Francis Catterson, Civil War Indiana Biographies"/> 

